A former French military base, Vauban is a thriving neighbourhood of 5,500 residents connected to Freiburg town centre by bus and light rail. Built in the late 1990s as a radical experiment in low-car living, it forgoes virtually all on-street parking in favour of active, green, and social spaces. üßµ

The street layout is built on the concept of ‚Äúfiltered permeability‚Äù, meaning the network geometry favours the active transport modes and filters out through motor traffic. As a result, 73% of movements are made by foot or bike, with the rate of car ownership just 183 per 1,000 people (and falling).

Most of Vauban's residential streets are described as stellplatzfrei‚Äîliterally ""free from parking spaces"". Motor vehicles are allowed down these streets at walking pace to pick up and deliver but not to park. At least a dozen shared cars are located in the district for residents to rent by the hour.

Two decades later, initial predictions Vauban residents would lament the loss of automobiles and abandon the experiment have proved false. Its popularity and quality-of-life remain remarkably high, as a shining example of a sustainable and prosperous community that can be been replicated globally. üîö
